               <msContents>
                  <summary>The Báb's Commentary on the Súratu'l-Baqara (Qur'án 2), unfinished: the
                     surviving text covers only the Fátiḥa and part of the second súra, breaking off
                     at v. 181 (f. 109b). Browne identifies this as the very Commentary whose
                     reading, according to an account in the Tárikh-i-Jadíd (quoted here in Persian
                     and English translation), converted Mullá Ḥuseyn of Bushraweyh to belief in the
                     Báb's mission.</summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="F_8-item1">
                     <author key="person_9878408" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9878408/">
                        <persName xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Bāb, ʻAlī Muḥammad
                           Shīrāzī, 1819-1850</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="ar">باب، ميرزا علي محمد</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" key="work_1840">Tafsīr sūrat al-baqarah</title>
                     <title xml:lang="ar" key="work_1840">تفسير سورة البقرة</title>
                     <title xml:lang="en" type="desc" key="work_1840">Commentary on the Súrat
                        al-Baqara</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="ar"/>
                     <explicit xml:lang="ar" defective="true"/>
                     <colophon>No title or colophon in the manuscript</colophon>
                     <note>The commentary opens with the Fátiḥa and a short commentary on it (quoted
                        by Browne in full), describing a sevenfold scheme of "Books" and "Gardens"
                        associated with Muḥammad, 'Alí, Fáṭima, Ḥasan, Ḥuseyn, Ja'far b. Muḥammad,
                        and Músá b. Ja'far. The commentary on the Súratu'l-Baqara itself then begins
                        without break, but ends at f. 109b with v. 181; Browne concludes "the rest
                        of the Commentary, therefore, would seem never to have been written."</note>
                     <note>Browne connects this work to the Tárikh-i-Jadíd's account (his own second
                        JRAS article on the Bábís, 1889, pp. 902-903) of Mullá Ḥuseyn of
                        Bushraweyh's conversion: reading an unattributed commentary on the
                        Súratu'l-Baqara, Mullá Ḥuseyn was struck by its singular merit, and on
                        pressing the reader (later revealed to be the Báb himself) learned it was
                        the work of "a mere youthful beginner" who nonetheless laid claim to great
                        knowledge. Browne notes he could not locate the specific phrase "<foreign
                           xml:lang="ar">تفسير باطن باطن</foreign>" mentioned in that account, and
                        that Ṣubḥ-i-Ezel told him it was in fact the Commentary on the Súra-i-Yúsuf
                        that convinced Mullá Ḥuseyn.</note>
                     <quote xml:lang="fa" cert="low" resp="#ocr-draft">بعد از ... در طاقچه چند جلد
                        کتاب بنظرم رسید برداشتم دیدم تفسیری است بی نظیر تعجب نمودم و پرسیدم این
                        تفسیر را که نوشته...</quote>
                     <incipit xml:lang="ar" cert="low" resp="#ocr-draft">بسم الله الرحمن الرحیم
                        الحمد لله رب العالمین... <locus from="2v" to="2v">(f. 2b)</locus></incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="ar" cert="low" resp="#ocr-draft">قال الله تعالی تلک امة قد
                        خلت لها ما کسبت و لکم ما کسبتم و لا تسئلون عما کانوا یعملون (<locus>v.
                           134</locus>, <locus from="109v" to="109v">f. 109b</locus>.</explicit>
                     <note>ending with verse 131 of Surat al-Baqara.</note>
                     <listBibl>
                        <bibl>
                           <ref target="https://cudl.lib.cam.ac.uk/view/PR-A-00233-00004/85"
                              >p.59</ref>
                        </bibl>
